<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08177h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08177h">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08177h"> 177(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> separate speech 8<sup>th</sup> cy</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">There is no record in history or tradition of a time when people in Ireland spoke anything but Gaelic. But the Picts, who, as the Venerable Bede tells us, kept their own distinct speech in the Britain of his day, the early part of the eighth century, were in Ireland also; and up to that same period they were recognised by the Gaels as a distinct people. <small> Stephen Gwynn, <a name="SGHI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SGHI"><cite title="source">The History of Ireland</cite></a> (1923) 3</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
